post_text:
Eureka City Schools is excited to announce that ALL children 18 and under, whether they attend an ECS school or not, can pick up meals at any of our 6 curbside locations at NO CHARGE! Alice Birney Elementary, Grant Elementary, Lafayette Elementary, Washington Elementary, Zane Middle School, and Eureka High School will have meals available Monday through Friday from 11 am - 1 pm through December 2020! (Please note that we are closed this Monday 9/7/20, in observance of the Labor Day holiday.)

*Please limit meal pickups to one site per day per child. Your child does NOT need to be present if you give our staff the ECS students' lunch ID number or if they don't attend an ECS school, the child's first and last name.

For any questions or clarifications contact (707)441-2501.

post_text:
Three local students have been named winners of a League of Women Voters of Humboldt County and KEET-TV sponsored ‚ÄúCelebrate the Vote‚Äù contest.

The winners are Rowan Dick from Alder Grove Charter School, who submitted her poem titled ‚ÄúYears‚Äù; Zoe LoCicero of Eureka High School, who entered her painting of suffragettes; and Gemma Caruso from Jacoby Creek School, who submitted her song, ‚ÄúWomen‚Äôs Right to Vote.‚Äù Each received $100 for their prize.

The contest was held in celebration of the 100th anniversary of the 19th Amendment, which guarantees women the right to vote. Students in grades four to 12 were asked to get creative by using a video, painting, drawing, poem, song or essay to show the importance of the 19th Amendment.

post_text: We have now completed our Electro Resistivity Testing and Ground Penetrating Radar Study of Albee Stadium, Bud Cloney Field, and the softball field. The point of the testing was to determine if there were any substantial voids in the ground caused by the failing drainage system posing a risk to the health and safety of our students and the community. Today, the ECS Maintenance Team, along with SHN Engineers & Geologists, excavated the ground in the areas with questionable readings. The preliminary results appear to be good news for our graduations planned to take place on July 30th (Zoe Barnum High School) and July 31st (Eureka High School). District staff has a meeting scheduled with Dr. Frankovich for the week of July 13th to determine what our graduation will look like. Think positive thoughts for an in-person graduation ceremony for the Class of 2020!

post_text:
A List of Books About Racism and Social Justice -
When your kids see demonstrations in the street or on the news as a response to racially charged incidents, you can help them understand what's going on by giving them some historical context. Sometimes such actions reflect a healthy democracy. Sometimes they lead to changing laws. Some movements are peaceful, others turn violent. These books tell stories of people's experiences of racism and of those who put their bodies on the line for the cause of equality under the law and social justice. The books are also grouped by age appropriateness. The list of books is provided by Common Sense Media (CSM), a non-profit organization that provides education and advocacy to families to promote safe technology and media for children.

A BIG THANK YOU TO OUR AMAZING BUS DRIVERS!!! For many students, school bus drivers often are the first school staff members they see each day. In addition to ensuring safe travel to and from school, bus drivers set the tone for the day, share encouraging words, and provide consistent and positive connections with our learners. We greatly appreciate this group of professionals for all they do for our students, families, and communities.

During the ordered shelter in place, bus drivers are working to make sure students have what they need to be successful in a remote learning environment. In addition to school meal pick-up programs, our bus drivers are providing meal delivery service along the bus routes. School bus drivers are making these deliveries so students are fed and focused on learning. We thank our school bus drivers and transportation professionals for the many ways they shape a student‚Äôs learning journey.

Please enjoy this video celebrating our amazing bus drivers!

post_text: Get help buying food while school is closed with Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), a new crisis-response beneÔ¨Åt. The P-EBT card is loaded with funds to purchase food and groceries. Families that are directly-certiÔ¨Åed for school meals through CalFresh, CalWORKS, Medi-Cal or social services DO NOT need to apply for P-EBT. These families should receive a new P-EBT card in the mail by May 22nd. Families eligible for free and reduced-price school meals through a school application and some attending schools where meals are free for all students will likely need to apply for P-EBT online between May 22nd and June 29th (apply online at ca.p-ebt.org). With schools closed due to #COVID19, children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals can get up to $365 in food benefits in addition to community ‚Äòto-go‚Äù meals. Learn more about these P-EBT food benefits here: https://ca.p-ebt.org/info. Also, please click on the comments for a handy Food Safety Guide.

Get emoji-tional with us and #ThankATeacher during Teacher Appreciation Week, May 4-8, 2020!

Teachers change the lives of millions of children every day‚Äîtheir immense work and impact moves us beyond words, so we need emojis to say how we feel. And with the abrupt end to the physical school year, our teachers have done even more to continue education with virtual classrooms and learning at home lessons. All to ensure every student has the tools they need to reach their full potential.

So, let‚Äôs all shower teachers in appreciation and share how we love (‚ù§Ô∏è) like (üëç), celebrate (üéâ) and care for (üòç) our teachers!

It's in these challenging times that we truly recognize and appreciate how our nation‚Äôs educators play such a pivotal role in our children‚Äôs lives‚Äîinspiring a lifelong love of learning and discovery and making a difference in their well-being and long-term success.

post_text: Families - If you would like to know more about the meals that are provided through the Free Meals Program for children 18 years old and younger, please visit eurekacityschools.nutrislice.com. You can learn carb counts as well as what might be included in the meals. Please note that meal contents may vary by site. If you have a smartphone, there is a Nutrislice app that can be downloaded for FREE through the apple store or google play, allowing you to have this information at your fingertips. As a reminder, the free meals are available Monday, Wednesday, and Friday from 11 am to 1 pm at our four elementary sites (Alice Birney, Grant, Lafayette, Washington) and Eureka High School. There are also meal deliveries on the morning bus routes every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. Please visit www.eurekacityschools.org for the school bus route and times. Meals for two days are provided every Monday and Wednesday. #eurekacityschools #schoolfoodservices #nutrislice

Eureka High School standout Jake Hanson was selected by the Green Bay Packers in the 2020 NFL Draft after starting at center for four years with the University of Oregon Ducks.

‚ÄúGrateful for the opportunity, Packers. Excited to start this next chapter!‚Äù Hanson wrote on Twitter.

Hanson joins the ranks of other notable Humboldters to be drafted into the NFL in the modern football era, including Eureka High School star Rey Maualuga, who was taken in the second round of the 2009 NFL Draft out of USC, and Humboldt State lineman Alex Cappa, who was taken in the 3rd Round of the 2018 NFL Draft by the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Congrats, Jake!

post_text: A BIG THANK YOU to our Afterschool Professionals! Afterschool Professionals Appreciation Week is a time to recognize and appreciate those who work with youth during out-of-school hours. It is a joint effort including community partners, afterschool programs, youth and child care workers, families and individuals. The week is marked by celebrations and public relations efforts to encourage people to thank afterschool professionals who make a difference in the lives of young people in their communities. Afterschool Professionals are skilled individuals who work with children and youth in diverse school and community-based settings to provide a wide variety of positive developmental relationships and experiences during out-of-school hours. Currently in the U.S., an estimated 850,000 individuals are practicing members of the afterschool profession.

HDN Schools to shine stadium lights for student athletes #BeTheLightHDN

HDN schools around the North Coast will turn on their stadium lights at 8:20 pm on Monday, April 20 to honor the senior class athletes of 2020 who had their seasons cut short due to COVID-19. The lights will stay on for 20 minutes.

This is not an event to attend, but a way to recognize the student-athletes of 2020. Students, their families, and the community are asked to keep the athletes and everyone impacted by COVID-19 in their thoughts.

As of Thursday night, Arcata, Del Norte, Eureka, Ferndale, Fortuna, McKinleyville and South Fork have all agreed to participate.

FREE Mini-Garden Sign-up! In order to make growing fresh food accessible for as many people as possible, Cooperation Humboldt is shifting its focus from larger lawn conversions to smaller mini-gardens. Their volunteers will deliver a semi-customized small garden setup to you at no charge. It is your responsibility to maintain your mini-garden (though they're happy to offer advice and support if needed.)

They are particularly interested in making these available to lower-income folks who would not otherwise be able to set one up on their own, and we ask that you decide for yourself whether you fit in that category or not. Please click on the link to apply!

Congratulations to Alissa Sarvinski, Eureka High School, for being chosen as a finalist for California Ag Educator of the Year!

Nationwide, the California Farm Bureau Federation and California FFA are proud to announce the following exceptional teachers as 2019-2020 Golden Owl Award finalists:
- Michael Campbell ‚Äì Imperial High School (Imperial FFA), Imperial, CA
- Rosemary Cummings ‚Äì Nipomo High School (Nipomo FFA), Nipomo, CA
- Andree‚Äô Earley ‚Äì Las Plumas High School (Las Plumas FFA), Oroville, CA
- Cody Jacobsen ‚Äì Golden Valley High School (Golden Valley FFA), Merced, CA
- Julie Luxon ‚Äì Madera South High School (Madera FFA), Madera, CA
- Alissa Sarvinski ‚Äì Eureka High School (Eureka FFA), Eureka, CA

Each finalist received an individualized plaque and $500 in funding for their program. Later this year, one finalist will be crowned California‚Äôs first Ag Educator of the Year and receive the coveted Golden Owl Award trophy and $3,000 in additional funding for their program. #CaliforniaFFA

post_text:
Thank you to James R Gensaw Sr. for sharing this good luck song during these uncertain times. Mr. Gensaw teaches four levels of the Yurok language to students at Eureka High School. Yurok is a Native American language that came close to extinction, as elders passed away. But Gensaw has played a key role in revitalizing the language. The Eureka Teachers Association member intertwines instruction with stories, songs and games, building a sense of community in the classroom. Approximately half of his students are Native American, and many are Yurok, but not all. While students say Yurok is easy to learn, it‚Äôs a complicated language ‚Äî for example, there are 20 different ways of counting, depending on whether one is counting animals, flat things, round things, money or people.
Yurok Tribe

post_text: Do you have the DRIVE to help kids? Then consider becoming a School Bus Driver! We will train the right person (social distancing protocol will be followed for all training)! Eureka City Schools, in beautiful Humboldt County, CA., has openings for two School Bus Drivers. If you love kids, are a hard worker, have a great attitude, a good driving record, and no drug or alcohol offenses in the past 5 years, contact Tiffany at 707.441.2503 to see if you might be a good fit. Do you already have all the qualifications necessary to be a School Bus Driver? Then just complete and submit an application! This position is 5.5 hrs/day, 5 days/wk, 181 days/yr (once school resumes) with the possibility of ‚Äúcombining‚Äù this position with another part-time position at Eureka City Schools if you want to work more hours. Use this link to access the job description and application process. Please share this post or tag someone if you think they might be interested or visit www.eurekacityschools.org for more great employment opportunities.

Susan Johnson

post_text: From the Marshall Family Resource Center: Only one of our sites, the District Office site, will be open while Eureka City Schools is shuttered. That site has alternate hours during the shutter, Monday-Thursday from 11 am - 3 pm. During this time an MFRC staff member will be available at the site by phone (707.441.2404) for resources and referrals. You can also access our food pantry, our hygiene supplies, laundry vouchers, and diapers during those hours. However, these services can only be accessed "curbside," as our site will only be open to the public by appointment so that we can ensure social distance and a safe, sanitized space. Both of our parenting classes, Nurturing Parent Program and the Parent Project, will be postponed until May 2020. Finally, on a limited basis, MFRC staff will be available to do outreach to families that do not have the means to access our site or their child's school site. Thank you for your patience during this unique situation.

post_text:
Update - Friday, March 13, 2020

Greetings Families,

Today has been another rapidly evolving day with issues related to planning for the coronavirus. We are continuing to be proactive in our efforts to plan for potential school closures. At this point, we still have no known students or staff with the coronavirus and we are continuing to work closely with the Humboldt County Department of Public Health. On Monday, we will have no school due to a planned professional development day for teachers. We will use a portion of this day for our planning for distance learning. Things are changing by the minute, so if we are asked to close schools over the weekend by our Governor or Public Health, we will update you as soon as possible. Please work to develop your home plan if we are forced to close schools.

Fred Van Vleck, Ed.D., Superintendent

Pi Day is celebrated on March 14th (3/14) around the world. Pi (Greek letter ‚ÄúœÄ‚Äù) is the symbol used in mathematics to represent a constant ‚Äî the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter ‚Äî which is approximately 3.14159. Pi Day is an annual opportunity for math enthusiasts to recite the infinite digits of Pi, talk to their friends about math, and to eat pie.Pi has been calculated to over one trillion digits beyond its decimal point. As an irrational and transcendental number, it will continue infinitely without repetition or pattern. While only a handful of digits are needed for typical calculations, Pi‚Äôs infinite nature makes it a fun challenge to memorize, and to computationally calculate more and more digits. To learn more about Pi, please see the comments for a link to an informative website.

post_text:
Important Message for Students/Families - March 12, 2020

Greetings all,

Guidance for a response to the coronavirus is evolving at a rapid pace. Early today, we were informed of new direction from the Office of Public Health advising the restriction of group gatherings in excess of 250 people for non-essential activities. However, this does not include schools and they are advising Eureka Schools to stay open. We still have no known cases of coronavirus amongst our staff or students. If you or your children have a fever or respiratory symptoms, please contact your primary medical provider for advice. At this point, we have canceled several events through March and school sites will be communicating out the specific events to you and/or your children. Please remember, schools will be closed on Monday, March 16th for staff professional development. As part of this professional development, staff will be planning for distance learning in the event of a school closure.

Fred Van Vleck, Superintendent

post_text:
Eureka City Schools is closely monitoring the coronavirus (COVID-19) and any occurrences within Humboldt County and our surrounding communities. Currently, there are no known or suspected cases of coronavirus within our District. However, we are taking action and coordinating efforts at our school sites to help prevent the spread of any illnesses. These precautionary measures include the following:

‚Ä¢ School staff are taking extra time to carefully sanitize school classrooms, common areas, and buses.

‚Ä¢ School staff are talking to students and reminding them
of the importance of washing their hands often and to cover any cough/sneeze with a tissue or sleeve.

‚Ä¢ Parents and guardians are also encouraged to speak to students to reinforce proper hand washing and make sure they are washing their hands often.

‚Ä¢ If your student is sick, please keep them at home. Students should not return to school until a fever has been gone for at least 24 hours without the use of fever-reducing medicines.

‚Ä¢ Eureka City Schools will keep students/families informed of any developments.

Eureka City Schools is closely monitoring the coronavirus (COVID-19) and any occurrences within Humboldt County and our surrounding communities. Currently, there are no known or suspected cases of coronavirus within our District. However, we are taking action and coordinating efforts at our school sites to help prevent the spread of any illnesses. These precautionary measures include the following:

‚Ä¢ School staff are taking extra time to carefully sanitize school classrooms, common areas, and buses.

‚Ä¢ School staff are talking to students and reminding them
of the importance of washing their hands often and to cover any cough/sneeze with a tissue or sleeve.

‚Ä¢ Parents and guardians are also encouraged to speak to students to reinforce proper hand washing and make sure they are washing their hands often.

‚Ä¢ If your student is sick, please keep them at home. Students should not return to school until a fever has been gone for at least 24 hours without the use of fever-reducing medicines.

‚Ä¢ Eureka City Schools will keep students/families informed of any developments.

post_text:
Today the Eureka High School Loggers Student-Athlete Advisory Council participated in the International Random Act of Kindness (RAK) Day. Their goal is to promote a positive relationship with a league member school off the playing field/court/mat. They put all their league schools' names in a hat and randomly draw which school will receive their RAK. This year the Fortuna Huskies were the chosen school. They called this year's RAK, "Hearts and Hugs for the Huskies" as this happened on Valentine's day. They served all their athletes hot chocolate, heart cookies, and Hershey hugs. They also combined the Husky Logo with the Logger logo to create a combined logo - "Huggers" (See picture attached). They ended up having more than enough to share with the Huskies so they headed over the bridge to Ferndale and handed out cookies and hot chocolate to classes and the office staff.
#YourStudentsYourSchoolsOurCommunity
#WeAreEurekaCitySchools

We called this year's RAK, "Hearts and Hugs for the Huskies" as this happened on Valentine's day. We served all their athletes hot chocolate, heart cookies, and Hershey hugs. We also combined the Husky Logo with the Logger logo to create a combined logo - "Huggers" (See picture attached)

We ended up having more than enough to share with the Huskies so we headed over the bridge to Ferndale and handed out cookies and hot chocolate to classes and the office staff.

post_text:
On February 6, 2020, the Governing Board presented an Apple Pin Award to Stephanie Escalante, a Literacy and English Learner Technician at Alice Birney Elementary! Stephanie was nominated by staff at Alice Birney Elementary and recognized for her dedication and service to students and families. Congratulations, Stephanie!

History of the Apple Pin Award: Apple Pins have been an award of gratitude given by the Board for more than 25 years. This Award has recognized those who have gone above and beyond as parent and community volunteers, good neighbors, Student Board Representatives, and Blue Collar, White Collar, Confidential, Administrative, and Certificated employees. A record of recipients was not started until 1992, but since then over 300 individuals have been awarded the Apple Pin.

post_text:
Learning the scientific process at Washington Elementary by doing a whole-class science experiment on surface tension. Surface tension is the tendency of fluid surfaces to shrink into the minimum surface area possible. Surface tension allows insects (e.g. water striders), usually denser than water, to float and slide on a water surface.

#WeAreEurekaCitySchools

Students at Zoe Barnum High School got to learn about the Trade of painting from Duane Hagans owner of CDH Painting, Inc.. Duane had a lot to share about painting, and also Duane shared his story of how he got into the trade. Duane reinforced that if someone is willing to work hard at their goals, they can do anything!

We're excited about the potential of the Trades Academy to grow and give more local students the opportunity to connect with trades industry craftsman and businesses. The Trades Academy is a key initiative in the Education At Work effort to bridge what students learn in their classrooms to their career or higher education success. With your help, we are making a difference in helping kids prepare for their futures, and supporting the development of our future workforce.
Thank you CDH Painting for an amazing day supporting these Zoe Barnum School s High students.

It's already the last week of January! ORDER NOW to make sure your Valentine gets a Singing Valentine and a rose! On February 13th and 14th, Limited Edition continues their decades-long tradition of Singing Valentines! Singers from Limited Edition will be performing at Eureka High School on the 13th and in the community on the 14th. This year the song "Good Lovin'" will be reintroduced as a classic Valentine. Each song is accompanied by a rose. A Singing Valentine is a great way to show how much you care. Give someone a rose and a song and join us in a Eureka High School tradition. Just $8 at on the EHS Campus on the 13th. On the 14th it's $15 in the city of Eureka and $20 outside of Eureka.
For more information, please call the choir office at (707)476-1757 or email youngc@eurekacityschools.org. Complete and return the attached form to EHS at 1915 J St, Eureka by Feb 11th. Please share this post or tag someone that might be interested! Thank you!

post_text: No school on Monday in honor of Martin Luther King, Jr. Martin Luther King Jr. was an American Christian minister and activist who became the most visible spokesperson and leader in the Civil Rights Movement from 1955 until his assassination in 1968. King was the youngest person to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964 and he was also awarded the Congressional Gold Medal and the Presidential Medal of Freedom. Have a fun and safe 3-day weekend!

post_text: Update on Status of School - Friday, January 17, 2020: All Eureka City School sites will remain OPEN during the power outage today. However, if your home is heated and you have the ability to keep your students home, we encourage you to do so. If you need to go to work, our schools will be open. It is important students come to school bundled up in multiple layers, as school sites will be cold. There are minimal lunch services today but snacks are available. If you are able to, please send your student with a lunch. Transportation services will continue as usual.

Local players turning heads at Olympic Development Program
text:
Last weekend, six players from Humboldt County traveled to Phoenix as part of the NorCal Olympic Development Program, an incredible number of local participants considering the prestigious nature of such an invite. Included were a trio of standouts from Eureka High School ‚Äî Keylei Carroll, Klayre Barres and Aquene Tollefson ‚Äî as well as Fortuna‚Äôs Sarah Killfoil, all four of them juniors and chosen for their age group‚Äôs 18-player roster, which features the very best players from throughout the entire Northern half of the state. Congratulations to all the players that were selected! Thank you to Humboldt Sports for the coverage!

The Eureka High School Student Government Class, in conjunction with the Intra-Club Council, recently organized the annual Thanksgiving Basket Program. Ten Eureka High School clubs/groups gathered items for eleven Thanksgiving Baskets that held all the necessary items for a fabulous Thanksgiving Feast including vegetables, mashed potatoes, desserts, and a gift certificate to be used to purchase a ham or turkey. These baskets were donated to the Marshall Family Resource Center and were distributed to families whose children attend a Eureka City Schools school. The clubs/groups that participated include: BSU, FFA, Interact, YEAH Club, DECA, Skills USA, Drama Club, AVID Club, Girls Power Club, and German Club.

post_text: First graders at Grant Elementary celebrated Day of the Dead yesterday by making Day of the Dead Bread using dough, sprinkles, and sugar from Los Bagels and baking them in a convection oven. Nearly everyone in Central and Southern Mexico enjoys Pan de Muerto‚Äîtranslated literally as "bread of the dead"‚Äîin early November as an important element of the annual Day of the Dead celebration. Most family and communal ofrendas (offerings for the beloved deceased) include at least one loaf left for the enjoyment of visiting souls. Many varieties of Pan de Muerto exist, with their shape, texture, and flavor particular to one or more geographical and cultural regions in Mexico. Depending on the area, you might find Pan de Muerto shaped like figures of people, animals, or in a crescent moon shape.

Most family and communal ofrendas (offerings for the beloved deceased) include at least one loaf left for the enjoyment of visiting souls. Many varieties of Pan de Muerto exist, with their shape, texture, and flavor particular to one or more geographical and cultural regions in Mexico. Depending on the area, you might find Pan de Muerto shaped like figures of people, animals, or in a crescent moon shape.

Grant Elementary
November 4, 2019 at 9:53 PM ¬∑

First grade celebrated Day of the Dead today by making Day of the Dead Bread using dough, sprinkles and sugar from Los Bagels and baking them in a convection oven. Yummy!

post_text: Congratulations to School Resource Officer (SRO) Chris Jenkins for being chosen as the Eureka Police Department's Officer of the Month for November! Eureka City Schools greatly appreciates Officer Jenkins' dedication to his job, the children, and his community!
shared_text:
Eureka Police Department
November 1, 2019 at 4:56 PM ¬∑

School Resource Officer (SRO) Chris Jenkins is November‚Äôs Officer of the Month! Officer Jenkins was selected by his supervisors for a number of different reasons but one of the main reasons was for how readily available he is. It is not uncommon for him to be called on his days off for various questions, concerns or issues and he never hesitates to come in on his days off if he is needed. He loves his position as SRO and handles all special events at the local schools. He loves the children he works with and facilitates a number of different projects, one of which assists getting children bicycles as needed. In addition to all that he does for the schools, he continues to assist patrol when staffing is low. Congratulations Officer Jenkins!

The Humboldt County Children's Author Festival began in 1975 to bring well-known published authors to Humboldt County and arrange visits to schools where they could talk with students about their love of reading, the craft of writing, and to reinforce the idea that people create books, and that children and students can also write and illustrate books.
Though the original goal was to host a one-time festival, its popularity with children, parents, teachers, librarians, and the general public was such that the festival evolved into a biennial event. Thank you to the amazing authors for visiting Eureka City Schools!

POSSIBLE PG&E POWER OUTAGE - INFORMATION FOR STUDENTS/FAMILIES

Eureka City Schools is monitoring the situation and will make the needed adjustments for the safety of all students. We will keep you updated with information as it becomes available to us.

At this time, all Eureka City Schools including Alice Birney, Grant, Lafayette, Washington, Winship, Zane, Eureka High School, Zoe Barnum, and the programs on the Lincoln Campus, will be open tomorrow regardless of whether or not power is on.

Please have your student dress in layers, as we will have no heat. If the power is out, please send your child to school with lunch and snacks as our cafeteria service will be limited. School sites will not have phones or email, so please drive to the school if you need to talk with your child or someone at the school. Communication with parents, if needed, will be sent home with students as our ability to call or email will be limited.

Last May and June students in grades 3-8 and grade 11 took the summative California Assessment of Student Performance and Progress (CAASPP) in English-language arts and mathematics. This is a statewide test that assesses students‚Äô mastery of grade-level standards. On October 1, 2019 the ECS Board of Trustees recognized 11 students who attained perfect scores on one or more of these tests. The Board presented the students with certificates acknowledging their outstanding achievements!
ELA Perfect Scores: Jacob Alston, Logan Bass, Marina Benson, Isabella Buckman, Sianna Shannon, Madison Sobilo, Jonathan Weatherby, Anastasia Young, Rina Ferroggiaro, Aeryonna Howton
Math Perfect Scores: Marina Benson, Jeremiah Thongchai
Congratulations!

#WeAreEurekaCitySchools

The first Wednesday in October makes a perfect time to celebrate National Walk Safely to School Day. Not only does the day encourage getting some exercise, but the weather is perfect for walking to school, too. Walking is one of the best forms of exercise. It isn‚Äôt hard on our joints and feet like running and jogging but still gives us all the advantages. The goal of this day is to raise awareness and support for the health, community and environmental benefits of regularly walking or biking to school. Yesterday, Lafayette Elementary's Leo the Lion and Kari the Cone escorted the students safely to school!
#YourStudentsYourSchoolsOurCommunity
#WeAreEurekaCitySchools

post_text:
Students from Eureka High School‚Äôs multicultural and Native American clubs came together last Friday to teach others about Native American culture and heritage. It was all in celebration of California Native American Day. At lunchtime, club members were dressed in traditional regalia and gave presentations on what each piece of clothing means and its cultural significance. Students were also able to try some native jellies and teas that were available. One club member says she loves being involved in events like this because she is Native American and loves sharing her culture with others. They will be holding a traditional brush dance performance and school wide assembly in November. Thank you to Redwood News for the great coverage!
#YourStudentsYourSchoolsOurCommunity
#WeAreEurekaCitySchools

post_text: Thank you, Humboldt State Men's Basketball! Grant Elementary appreciates your time and dedication! Good luck with your season!
shared_text:
HSUJACKS.COM
Lumberjacks‚Äô Men‚Äôs Basketball Community Outreach Program-Grant Elementary School - Humboldt State University Athletics

Grant Elementary
September 26, 2019 at 10:07 AM ¬∑

The Humboldt State Men's Basketball team conducted a community outreach program at Grant Elementary School yesterday for over 200 kids ranging from kindergarten to fifth grade. The elementary kids were able to connect and develop new relationships with the college student-athletes during lunchtime and out on the playground. The Lumberjacks spoke to the kids emphasizing safe, respectable, and responsible play and stressing the importance regarding academics in the classroom. The 'Jacks performed fundamental drills ranging from ball handling and passing to spectacular slam dunks while the kids cheered from the sidelines. The student-athletes also taught basketball skill development on the playground and signed autographs before the kids returned to the classroom. The Lumberjacks were represented by two international student-athletes, Victor Mijas from Brazil and Gabrys Sadaunkyas from Lithuania, Arash Poorsina from San Francisco, and Ruben Parks, Jr. from Fresno. Thank you to Humboldt State University for the program and the write-up!

post_text: Eureka High School junior Keylei Carroll is known for her great defensive play, anchoring a strong Loggers back line alongside Rebecca Russ. But on Saturday, Carroll showed the other side to her game with a brilliant scoring header off a perfectly placed corner kick by Brynn Hales to seal a hard-fought 2-0 win at rivals Arcata.The win gives the Loggers some crucial early momentum in the H-DNL race, and wasn‚Äôt secured until Carroll headed home in the final minute of play. And what a header it was, with Carroll blasting the ball into the roof of the net and giving Arcata goalie Skaidra Pulley and her defense no chance. ‚ÄúFor any team at any level, that was a beautiful goal,‚Äù Arcata head coach Patrick Stranahan said. The assist was Hales‚Äô second of the game. Thank you to Humboldt Sports for the great write-up and coverage!

Eureka High School junior Keylei Carroll is known for her great defensive play, anchoring a strong Loggers back line alongside Rebecca Russ. But on Saturday, Carroll showed the other side to her game with a brilliant scoring header off a perfectly placed corner kick by Brynn Hales to seal a hard-fought 2-0 win at rivals Arcata.The win gives the Loggers some crucial early momentum in the H-DNL race, and wasn‚Äôt secured until Carroll headed home in the final minute of play. And what a header it was, with Carroll blasting the ball into the roof of the net and giving Arcata goalie Skaidra Pulley and her defense no chance. ‚ÄúFor any team at any level, that was a beautiful goal,‚Äù Arcata head coach Patrick Stranahan said. The assist was Hales‚Äô second of the game. Thank you to Humboldt Sports for the great write-up and coverage!
